Cyclistic Bike-Share

John Gimlin

July 2021


A Case Study: How Does a Bike-Share Navigate Speedy Success?


Google Data Analyst Certification Capstone Project


Background
This project involves a fictional bike-share company, Cyclistic. The data used for analysis is publicly available from divvy, the real-world city of Chicago bike-share operator.

Objective
Maximize the number of annual subscriptions by turning casual customers into members. The specific goal of this project is to understand how casual riders and annual members use Cyclistic bikes differently.

Phase 1: Import Data

Phase 2: Clean data

# Change data types of start_station_id and end_station_id in older files to match newer files

aug20$end_station_id <- as.character(aug20$end_station_id)
sep20$start_station_id <- as.character(sep20$start_station_id)
sep20$end_station_id <- as.character(sep20$end_station_id)

oct20$end_station_id <- as.character(oct20$end_station_id)

# Clean column names
combined %>% clean_names()

# Drop any duplicate rows
combined <- combined %>% distinct() # Removed 0 rows

# Drop rows with NA values
combined <- drop_na(combined) # Removed 314,299 rows

# Check size resulting data frame
dim(combined) # 13 cols by 3,759,262 rows
[1] 3759262      13

Phase 3: Modify data for analysis

# Add new column for ride month
combined$month <- month(combined$started_at, label= TRUE)

# Add new column for ride day of week
combined$weekday <- wday(combined$started_at, label= TRUE)

# Add new column for ride_duration in seconds
combined <- mutate(combined, "ride_duration"= ended_at - started_at)

# Remove rows with ride_duration less than 1 minute (indicating maintenance or user error)
combined <- combined %>% filter(ride_duration > 60) # removed 59,813 rows

#Add column for ride distance (in meters)
combined$distance <- distGeo(matrix(c(combined$start_lng, combined$start_lat), ncol = 2),
                             matrix(c(combined$end_lng, combined$end_lat), ncol = 2))

# Convert to km
combined$distance <- combined$distance / 1000

# Add column for ride speed in km/hr
combined$speed = c(combined$distance) / as.numeric(c(combined$ride_duration), units = "hours")

# Verify new columns and formulas
combined[sample(nrow(combined), 5),  c(3, 14:18)]

# Create data frame for rides by customer type
rides_by_customer <- combined %>% 
  group_by(member_casual) %>% 
  summarise("num_rides"= n(), "avg_ride_duration"= mean(ride_duration),
            "avg_ride_distance"= mean(distance), "avg_speed"= mean(speed),
            .groups= "drop")
rides_by_customer
# Plot number of rides by customer type
ggplot(data= rides_by_customer) +
  geom_col(mapping= aes(x= member_casual, y= num_rides, fill= member_casual),
           show.legend= FALSE) +
  scale_fill_manual(values= c("orange", "dodgerblue")) +
  labs(title= "Number of Rides by Customer Type", x= "Customer Type",
       y= "Number of Rides")

# Plot avg. ride duration
ggplot(data= rides_by_customer) +

           show.legend= FALSE) +
  scale_fill_manual(values= c("orange", "dodgerblue")) +
  labs(title= "Average Ride Duration by Customer Type", x= "Customer Type",
       y= "Avg. Ride Duration (sec.)")

combined %>% 
  group_by(month, rideable_type) %>% 
  summarise(num_trips = n(), .groups= "drop")
# classic_bike and docked_bike are classifications of the same bike type

# Combine classic and docked bike types
rides_by_bike <- combined %>% 
  group_by(member_casual) %>% 
  summarise(classic_bike = sum(rideable_type == "classic_bike" |
                                   rideable_type == "docked_bike"),
            electric_bike = sum(rideable_type == "electric_bike"))
`summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)
rides_by_bike

# Pivot so we can plot
rbb_longer <- rides_by_bike %>% 
  pivot_longer(classic_bike:electric_bike, names_to= "bike_type",
               values_to= "num_rides")
rbb_longer

# Plot number rides by bike type by customer
ggplot(rbb_longer) +
  geom_col(mapping= aes(x= bike_type, y= num_rides, fill= member_casual),
           position= "dodge") +
  scale_fill_manual(values= c("orange", "dodgerblue")) +
  labs(title= "Rides by Bike Type & Customer Type", x= "Bike Type", 
       y= "Number of Rides", fill= "Customer: ") +
  theme(legend.position= "top")

Phase 5: Map data

# Create data frames for most frequented stations by customer 

# Casual Top 70 START Stations (equates to top 10% of ~700 stations total)
most_pop_cas_start_sta <- combined %>% 
  filter(member_casual == "casual") %>% 
  group_by(start_station_name) %>% 
  summarise("num_rides" = n(), "lat"= mean(start_lat), "lng"= mean(start_lng),
            .groups= "drop") %>% 
  arrange(desc(num_rides)) %>% 
  head(70)

# Casual Top 70 END Stations
most_pop_cas_end_sta <- combined %>% 
  filter(member_casual == "casual") %>% 
  group_by(end_station_name) %>% 
  summarise("num_rides" = n(), "lat"= mean(end_lat), "lng"= mean(end_lng),
            .groups= "drop") %>% 
  arrange(desc(num_rides)) %>% 
  head(70)

# Member Top 70 START Stations
most_pop_mem_start_sta <- combined %>% 
  filter(member_casual == "member") %>% 
  group_by(start_station_name) %>% 
  summarise("num_rides" = n(), "lat"= mean(start_lat), "lng"= mean(start_lng),
            .groups= "drop") %>% 
  arrange(desc(num_rides)) %>% 
  head(70)

# Member Top 70 END Stations
most_pop_mem_end_sta <- combined %>% 
  filter(member_casual == "member") %>%
